        <div class="row">
            <ul> <h4><strong>How the SBW connects with the previous 4 stereotypes?</strong></h4>
                <li>Mammy: paints Black women as "emotionally resilient providers and caregivers who need no help" based on the idea they are strong and independent</li>
                <li>Jezebel: shifted the narrative to having Black women without emotions from being seen as hypersexualized and more as objects than as humans</li>
                <li>Sapphire: forces women to overexert themselves mentally, physically, emotionally, and socially at the expense of her mental health to conform to society’s idea of Black womanhood</li>
                <li>Welfare Queen: According to Patricia Hill Collins, the Matriarch is "a single Black working woman with children."She is depicted as unfeminine because she is career-oriented and is considered a bad mother and a failure for not being in the home to supervise and help the children with school assignments.  This image places the blame of all ills facing the Black community on the Black woman, and this contributes to the perception that Black women are responsible for the ills that the Black family faces such as "poverty [and] joblessness"</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

